The medic stares at my sore scalp through cracked lenses. There are frail tweezers and alcohol, rusty syringes aligned between two poetry books, intermittently blinking monitors looking like long-abandoned miniature aquariums, vials of expired drugs in half-rotten cardboard boxes, a row of crimson-glazed ants marching past the abandoned decanters like a conquering army&mdash;
&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t think you&rsquo;ve been honest with me&hellip;&rdquo;
On the veranda, a chrysanthemum flower blooms like a flesh wound, its petals stretching across the windows.
